snippet.textDisplay: Pythagorean theorem is calculating the longest side of the triangle, used for right triangles, basically                          c2 = a2 + b2 put the 2 numbers of  the 2 sides that you have so for example c(2) = 3(2) + 4(2)            [(2) in a bracket means exponent, like number power to 2, so if its 7 then 7 multiply 7, not 7 multiply 2] so continuing, we get c(2) = 9 + 16, which is c(2) = 25,   then we have to make sure the (c) that we are solving for is the only thing that remains on one side and everything else on one side, because then that's the value of (c) so now we bring exponent of 2 to the other side and it becomes,     /c(2)      "/" cancels "2" and c is now free of everything, and the "/" also goes to the 25 on the other side and 25 is square rooted, meaning that if 5 multiply 5 is 25 then the square root of 25 is 5, same with 81, 9 multiply 9 is 81, so 9 is the square root of 81, now your done, the answer of the longest side is 5, c = 5. Simple.
